# Orca Community Edition — Team Workflow Guide

When a team member wants to submit work, push changes, create a PR, or merge to main, guide them through the correct workflow based on their role.

## Step 1: Identify the Team Member

Ask who they are or check git config:

```bash
git config user.name
git remote -v
```

| Member | Role | Branch | Workflow |
|--------|------|--------|----------|
| Sivaji (@sivaji-orca) | Owner | dev/sivaji | Push directly to dev/sivaji, PR to main |
| Sathish (@sathish-aidev) | Contributor | dev/sathish | Fork-based, PR to dev/sathish |
| Rajiv (TBD) | Contributor | dev/rajiv | Fork-based, PR to dev/rajiv |

If `origin` points to `sivaji-orca/orca-community`, they're the owner.
If `origin` points to a fork, they're a contributor.

## Step 2: For the Owner (Sivaji)

### Submitting work to dev/sivaji

```bash
# Make sure you're on dev/sivaji
git checkout dev/sivaji

# If working on a feature branch, merge it
git merge feature/your-feature
git push origin dev/sivaji
```

### Merging dev/sivaji to main

```bash
# Create a PR from dev/sivaji to main
gh pr create --base main --head dev/sivaji --title "feat: description of changes"

# Or via GitHub UI:
# 1. Go to https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community/compare/main...dev/sivaji
# 2. Create PR, wait for CI, merge
```

### Reviewing contributor PRs

```bash
# List open PRs
gh pr list

# Review a specific PR
gh pr view <number>
gh pr review <number> --approve
gh pr merge <number> --squash
```

### Syncing dev branches after merging to main

After merging any dev branch to main, sync all dev branches:

```bash
git checkout main && git pull
git checkout dev/sivaji && git rebase main && git push origin dev/sivaji --force-with-lease
git checkout dev/sathish && git rebase main && git push origin dev/sathish --force-with-lease
git checkout dev/rajiv && git rebase main && git push origin dev/rajiv --force-with-lease
```

## Step 3: For Contributors (Sathish, Rajiv)

### Verify fork setup

```bash
# Check remotes
git remote -v
# origin should point to YOUR fork
# upstream should point to sivaji-orca/orca-community

# If upstream is missing:
git remote add upstream https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community.git
```

### Creating a feature branch

```bash
# Sync your dev branch first
git checkout dev/<your-name>
git fetch upstream
git rebase upstream/dev/<your-name>

# Create feature branch
git checkout -b fix/descriptive-name
```

Branch naming: `fix/`, `feature/`, `docs/`, `dx/`, `refactor/`, `test/`

### Submitting a PR

```bash
# Test everything first
cd backend && bun test
cd ../frontend && bun run test && bun run lint

# Commit with conventional format
git add -A
git commit -m "fix(backend): resolve port 3003 conflict"

# Push to your fork
git push origin fix/descriptive-name
```

Then create a PR:
- **Base repo**: `sivaji-orca/orca-community`
- **Base branch**: `dev/<your-name>` (NOT main!)
- **Head**: your fork's feature branch

Or via CLI:
```bash
gh pr create --repo sivaji-orca/orca-community --base dev/<your-name> --head <your-username>:fix/descriptive-name
```

### Important: PR goes to your dev branch, NOT main

Contributors should NEVER PR directly to `main`. Always target your `dev/<name>` branch. The owner will merge dev to main when a batch of work is ready.

## Step 4: After PR is Merged

### Clean up

```bash
# Delete the feature branch locally
git checkout dev/<your-name>
git branch -d fix/descriptive-name

# Delete from your fork
git push origin --delete fix/descriptive-name

# Sync your dev branch
git fetch upstream
git rebase upstream/dev/<your-name>
```

## Quick Reference

| Action | Owner (Sivaji) | Contributor (Sathish/Rajiv) |
|--------|---------------|----------------------------|
| Work on | `dev/sivaji` | Fork + feature branches |
| PR target | `main` | `dev/<name>` |
| Review PRs | Yes (all) | No (only own work) |
| Merge to main | Yes | No (owner does this) |
| Sync after merge | Rebase all dev branches | `git fetch upstream && git rebase` |
